Looking for a quick and tasty midweek dinner option? Try cooking up our Speedy Pork and Bacon Penne in just 20 minutes for a delicious and speedy meal.

== Pasta ==

Bring a #large saucepan{} of water to the boil on high heat with @salt{1/2%tsp}.

Heat a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil). Once hot, add the @British smoked bacon lardons{90%g}. Stir-fry until golden, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. Cook bacon thoroughly.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}), then add to the @British pork mince{240%g} with the @mixed herbs{1}. Cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}.

Meanwhile, add the @penne pasta{180%g} to the pan of boiling water and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back into the pan. Drizzle with oil and stir through to stop it sticking together.

== Sauce ==

While the pasta cooks, add the @Worcester sauce{15%ml} to the pork and allow to bubble away until evaporated, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in the @finely chopped tomatoes with onion and garlic{1}(400g can), @red wine stock paste{28%g}, @water for the sauce{50%ml} and a @?sugar{pinch}.

Bring to the boil, stirring, then reduce the heat to medium and simmer until the sauce has thickened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> Add a splash of water if it gets too thick. The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

== Finishing ==

Meanwhile, grate the @mature cheddar cheese{30%g}.

When the sauce has thickened, add the @baby spinach{40%g} a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Toss the cooked penne through the sauce along with the grated Cheddar and combine well.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} if needed.

When ready, serve your pork and bacon penne in #bowls{}. Enjoy!